# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: certificate-lifecycle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In cryptography, a **certificate authority** or **certification authority** (**CA**) is an entity that stores, signs, and issues digital certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made about the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] A CA acts as a trusted third party—trusted both by the subject (owner) of the certificate and by the party relying upon the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The format of these certificates is specified by the X.509 or EMV standard.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] One particularly common use for certificate authorities is to sign certificates used in HTTPS, the secure browsing protocol for the World Wide Web.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Another common use is in issuing identity cards by national governments for use in electronically signing documents.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Trusted certificates can be used to create secure connections to a server via the Internet.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] A certificate is essential in order to circumvent a malicious party which happens to be on the route to a target server which acts as if it were the target.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Such a scenario is commonly referred to as a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The client uses the CA certificate to authenticate the CA signature on the server certificate, as part of the authorizations before launching a secure connection.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Usually, client software—for example, browsers—include a set of trusted CA certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This makes sense, as many users need to trust their client software.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] A malicious or compromised client can skip any security check and still fool its users into believing otherwise.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The clients of a CA are server supervisors who call for a certificate that their servers will bestow to users.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Commercial CAs charge money to issue certificates, and their customers anticipate the CA's certificate to be contained within the majority of web browsers, so that safe connections to the certified servers work efficiently out-of-the-box.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The quantity of web browsers, other devices, and applications which trust a particular certificate authority is referred to as ubiquity.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Mozilla, which is a non-profit business, issues several commercial CA certificates with its products.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] While Mozilla developed their own policy, the CA/Browser Forum developed similar guidelines for CA trust.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] A single CA certificate may be shared among multiple CAs or their resellers.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] A *root* CA certificate may be the base to issue multiple *intermediate* CA certificates with varying validation requirements.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In addition to commercial CAs, some non-profits issue publicly-trusted digital certificates without charge, for example Let's Encrypt.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Some large cloud computing and web hosting companies are also publicly-trusted CAs and issue certificates to services hosted on their infrastructure, for example IBM Cloud, Amazon Web Services, Cloudflare, and Google Cloud Platform.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Large organizations or government bodies may have their own PKIs (public key infrastructure), each containing their own CAs.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Any site using self-signed certificates acts as its own CA.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Each payment card presents along with its card data also the Card Issuer Certificate to the POS.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The Issuer Certificate is signed by EMV CA Certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The POS retrieves the public key of EMV CA from its storage, validates the Issuer Certificate and authenticity of the payment card before sending the payment request to the payment scheme.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Browsers and other clients of sorts characteristically allow users to add or do away with CA certificates at will.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] While server certificates regularly last for a relatively short period, CA certificates are further extended, so, for repeatedly visited servers, it is less error-prone importing and trusting the CA issued, rather than confirm a security exemption each time the server's certificate is renewed.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Less often, trustworthy certificates are used for encrypting or signing messages.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] CAs dispense end-user certificates too, which can be used with S/MIME.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] However, encryption entails the receiver's public key and, since authors and receivers of encrypted messages, apparently, know one another, the usefulness of a trusted third party remains confined to the signature verification of messages sent to public mailing lists.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Worldwide, the certificate authority business is fragmented, with national or regional providers dominating their home market.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This is because many uses of digital certificates, such as for legally binding digital signatures, are linked to local law, regulations, and accreditation schemes for certificate authorities.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] However, the market for globally trusted TLS/SSL server certificates is largely held by a small number of multinational companies.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This market has significant barriers to entry due to the technical requirements.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] While not legally required, new providers may choose to undergo annual security audits (such as WebTrust for certificate authorities in North America and ETSI in Europe) to be included as a trusted root by a web browser or operating system.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] As of 24 August 2020, 147 root certificates, representing 52 organizations, are trusted in the Mozilla Firefox web browser, 168 root certificates, representing 60 organizations, are trusted by macOS, and 255 root certificates, representing 101 organizations, are trusted by Microsoft Windows.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] As of Android 4.2 (Jelly Bean), Android currently contains over 100 CAs that are updated with each release.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Let's Encrypt is operated by the newly formed Internet Security Research Group, a California nonprofit recognized as federally tax-exempt.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The top spot has been held by Symantec (or VeriSign before it was purchased by Symantec) ever since [our] survey began, with it currently accounting for just under a third of all certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] As of July 2024 the survey company W3Techs, which collects statistics on certificate authority usage among the Alexa top 10 million and the Tranco top 1 million websites, lists the five largest authorities by absolute usage share as below.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The commercial CAs that issue the bulk of certificates for HTTPS servers typically use a technique called "domain validation" to authenticate the recipient of the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The techniques used for domain validation vary between CAs, but in general domain validation techniques are meant to prove that the certificate applicant controls a given domain name, not any information about the applicant's identity.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Many Certificate Authorities also offer Extended Validation (EV) certificates as a more rigorous alternative to domain validated certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Extended validation is intended to verify not only control of a domain name, but additional identity information to be included in the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Some browsers display this additional identity information in a green box in the URL bar.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Domain validation suffers from certain structural security limitations.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In particular, it is always vulnerable to attacks that allow an adversary to observe the domain validation probes that CAs send.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] These can include attacks against the DNS, TCP, or BGP protocols (which lack the cryptographic protections of TLS/SSL), or the compromise of routers.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Such attacks are possible either on the network near a CA, or near the victim domain itself.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] One of the most common domain validation techniques involves sending an email containing an authentication token or link to an email address that is likely to be administratively responsible for the domain.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This could be the technical contact email address listed in the domain's WHOIS entry, or an administrative email like admin@, administrator@, webmaster@, hostmaster@ or postmaster@ the domain.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Some Certificate Authorities may accept confirmation using root@, info@, or support@ in the domain.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The theory behind domain validation is that only the legitimate owner of a domain would be able to read emails sent to these administrative addresses.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Domain validation implementations have sometimes been a source of security vulnerabilities.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In one instance, security researchers showed that attackers could obtain certificates for webmail sites because a CA was willing to use an email address like ssladmin@domain.com for domain.com, but not all webmail systems had reserved the "ssladmin" username to prevent attackers from registering it.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Prior to 2011, there was no standard list of email addresses that could be used for domain validation, so it was not clear to email administrators which addresses needed to be reserved.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The first version of the CA/Browser Forum Baseline Requirements, adopted November 2011, specified a list of such addresses.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This allowed mail hosts to reserve those addresses for administrative use, though such precautions are still not universal.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In January 2015, a Finnish man registered the username "hostmaster" at the Finnish version of Microsoft Live and was able to obtain a domain-validated certificate for live.fi, despite not being the owner of the domain name.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] A CA issues digital certificates that contain a public key and the identity of the owner.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The matching private key is not made available publicly, but kept secret by the end user who generated the key pair.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The certificate is also a confirmation or validation by the CA that the public key contained in the certificate belongs to the person, organization, server or other entity noted in the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] A CA's obligation in such schemes is to verify an applicant's credentials, so that users and relying parties can trust the information in the issued certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] CAs use a variety of standards and tests to do so.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In essence, the certificate authority is responsible for saying "yes, this person is who they say they are, and we, the CA, certify that".
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] If the user trusts the CA and can verify the CA's signature, then they can also assume that a certain public key does indeed belong to whoever is identified in the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Public-key cryptography can be used to encrypt data communicated between two parties.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This can typically happen when a user logs on to any site that implements the HTTP Secure protocol.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In this example let us suppose that the user logs on to their bank's homepage www.bank.example to do online banking.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] When the user opens www.bank.example homepage, they receive a public key along with all the data that their web-browser displays.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The rest of the communication then proceeds using the new (disposable) symmetric key, so when the user enters some information to the bank's page and submits the page (sends the information back to the bank) then the data the user has entered to the page will be encrypted by their web browser.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Therefore, even if someone can access the (encrypted) data that was communicated from the user to www.bank.example, such eavesdropper cannot read or decipher it.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This mechanism is only safe if the user can be sure that it is the bank that they see in their web browser.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] If the user types in www.bank.example, but their communication is hijacked and a fake website (that pretends to be the bank website) sends the page information back to the user's browser, the fake web-page can send a fake public key to the user (for which the fake site owns a matching private key).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The user will fill the form with their personal data and will submit the page.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The fake web-page will then get access to the user's data.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This is what the certificate authority mechanism is intended to prevent.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] A certificate authority (CA) is an organization that stores public keys and their owners, and every party in a communication trusts this organization (and knows its public key).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] When the user's web browser receives the public key from www.bank.example it also receives a digital signature of the key (with some more information, in a so-called X.509 certificate).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The browser already possesses the public key of the CA and consequently can verify the signature, trust the certificate and the public key in it: since www.bank.example uses a public key that the certification authority certifies, a fake www.bank.example can only use the same public key.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Since the fake www.bank.example does not know the corresponding private key, it cannot create the signature needed to verify its authenticity.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] It is difficult to assure correctness of match between data and entity when the data are presented to the CA (perhaps over an electronic network), and when the credentials of the person/company/program asking for a certificate are likewise presented.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This is why commercial CAs often use a combination of authentication techniques including leveraging government bureaus, the payment infrastructure, third parties' databases and services, and custom heuristics.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In some enterprise systems, local forms of authentication such as Kerberos can be used to obtain a certificate which can in turn be used by external relying parties.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Notaries are required in some cases to personally know the party whose signature is being notarized; this is a higher standard than is reached by many CAs.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] 2. a contract relating to such transaction may not be denied legal effect, validity or enforceability solely because an electronic signature or electronic record was used in its formation.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Despite the security measures undertaken to correctly verify the identities of people and companies, there is a risk of a single CA issuing a bogus certificate to an imposter.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] It is also possible to register individuals and companies with the same or very similar names, which may lead to confusion.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] To minimize this hazard, the *certificate transparency* initiative proposes auditing all certificates in a public unforgeable log, which could help in the prevention of phishing.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In large-scale deployments, Alice may not be familiar with Bob's certificate authority (perhaps they each have a different CA server), so Bob's certificate may also include his CA's public key signed by a different CA2, which is presumably recognizable by Alice.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This process typically leads to a hierarchy or mesh of CAs and CA certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, which signals that it is no longer valid.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or misissued certificate until expiry.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Hence, revocation is an important part of a public key infrastructure.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Revocation is performed by the issuing CA, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] For distributing revocation information to clients, timeliness of the discovery of revocation (and hence the window for an attacker to exploit a compromised certificate) trades off against resource usage in querying revocation statuses and privacy concerns.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] If revocation information is unavailable (either due to accident or an attack), clients must decide whether to *fail-hard* and treat a certificate as if it is revoked (and so degrade availability) or to *fail-soft* and treat it as unrevoked (and allow attackers to sidestep revocation).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Due to the cost of revocation checks and the availability impact from potentially-unreliable remote services, Web browsers limit the revocation checks they will perform, and will fail-soft where they do.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Certificate revocation lists are too bandwidth-costly for routine use, and the Online Certificate Status Protocol presents connection latency and privacy issues.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Other schemes have been proposed but have not yet been successfully deployed to enable fail-hard checking.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The CA/Browser Forum publishes the Baseline Requirements, a list of policies and technical requirements for CAs to follow.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] These are a requirement for inclusion in the certificate stores of Firefox and Safari.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] On April 14, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum passed a ballot to reduce SSL/TLS certificates to 47 day maximum term by March 15, 2029.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] If the CA can be subverted, then the security of the entire system is lost, potentially subverting all the entities that trust the compromised CA.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] For example, suppose an attacker, Eve, manages to get a CA to issue to her a certificate that claims to represent Alice.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] That is, the certificate would publicly state that it represents Alice, and might include other information about Alice.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Some of the information about Alice, such as her employer name, might be true, increasing the certificate's credibility.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Eve, however, would have the all-important private key associated with the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Eve could then use the certificate to send a digitally signed email to Bob, tricking Bob into believing that the email was from Alice.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Bob might even respond with encrypted email, believing that it could only be read by Alice, when Eve is actually able to decrypt it using the private key.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] A notable case of CA subversion like this occurred in 2001, when the certificate authority VeriSign issued two certificates to a person claiming to represent Microsoft.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The certificates have the name "Microsoft Corporation", so they could be used to spoof someone into believing that updates to Microsoft software came from Microsoft when they actually did not.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Microsoft and VeriSign took steps to limit the impact of the problem.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In 2008, Comodo reseller Certstar sold a certificate for mozilla.com to Eddy Nigg, who had no authority to represent Mozilla.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In 2011 fraudulent certificates were obtained from Comodo and DigiNotar, allegedly by Iranian hackers.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] There is evidence that the fraudulent DigiNotar certificates were used in a man-in-the-middle attack in Iran.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In 2012, it became known that Trustwave issued a subordinate root certificate that was used for transparent traffic management (man-in-the-middle) which effectively permitted an enterprise to sniff SSL internal network traffic using the subordinate certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In 2012, the Flame malware (also known as SkyWiper) contained modules that had an MD5 collision with a valid certificate issued by a Microsoft Terminal Server licensing certificate that used the broken MD5 hash algorithm.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The authors thus was able to conduct a collision attack with the hash listed in the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] In 2015, a Chinese certificate authority named MCS Holdings and affiliated with China's central domain registry issued unauthorized certificates for Google domains.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Google thus removed both MCS and the root certificate authority from Chrome and have revoked the certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] An attacker who steals a certificate authority's private keys is able to forge certificates as if they were CA, without needed ongoing access to the CA's systems.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Key theft is therefore one of the main risks certificate authorities defend against.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Publicly trusted CAs almost always store their keys on a hardware security module (HSM), which allows them to sign certificates with a key, but generally prevent extraction of that key with both physical and software controls.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] CAs typically take the further precaution of keeping the key for their long-term root certificates in an HSM that is kept offline, except when it is needed to sign shorter-lived intermediate certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The intermediate certificates, stored in an online HSM, can do the day-to-day work of signing end-entity certificates and keeping revocation information up to date.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] CAs sometimes use a key ceremony when generating signing keys, in order to ensure that the keys are not tampered with or copied.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The critical weakness in the way that the current X.509 scheme is implemented is that any CA trusted by a particular party can then issue certificates for any domain they choose.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Such certificates will be accepted as valid by the trusting party whether they are legitimate and authorized or not.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This is a serious shortcoming given that the most commonly encountered technology employing X.509 and trusted third parties is the HTTPS protocol.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] As all major web browsers are distributed to their end-users pre-configured with a list of trusted CAs that numbers in the dozens this means that any one of these pre-approved trusted CAs can issue a valid certificate for any domain whatsoever.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] The industry response to this has been muted.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] Given that the contents of a browser's pre-configured trusted CA list is determined independently by the party that is distributing or causing to be installed the browser application there is really nothing that the CAs themselves can do.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] This issue is the driving impetus behind the development of the DNS-based Authentication of Named Entities (DANE) protocol.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-authority] If adopted in conjunction with Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) DANE will greatly reduce if not eliminate the role of trusted third parties in a domain's PKI.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] In cryptography, a **certificate revocation list** (**CRL**) is "a list of digital certificates that have been revoked by the issuing certificate authority (CA) before their scheduled expiration date and should no longer be trusted".
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] Publicly trusted CAs in the Web PKI are required (including by the CA/Browser forum) to issue CRLs for their certificates, and they widely do.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] Browsers and other relying parties might use CRLs, or might use alternate certificate revocation technologies (such as OCSP) or CRLSets (a dataset derived from CRLs) to check certificate revocation status.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] Note that OCSP is falling out of favor due to privacy and performance concerns, resulting in a return to CRLs.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] Subscribers and other parties can also use ARI.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] A certificate is irreversibly revoked if, for example, it is discovered that the certificate authority (CA) had improperly issued a certificate, or if a private-key is thought to have been compromised.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] Certificates may also be revoked for failure of the identified entity to adhere to policy requirements, such as publication of false documents, misrepresentation of software behaviour, or violation of any other policy specified by the CA operator or its customer.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] The most common reason for revocation is the user no longer being in sole possession of the private key (e.g., the token containing the private key has been lost or stolen).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] This reversible status can be used to note the temporary invalidity of the certificate (e.g., if the user is unsure if the private key has been lost).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] If, in this example, the private key was found and nobody had access to it, the status could be reinstated, and the certificate is valid again, thus removing the certificate from future CRLs.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] A CRL is generated and published periodically, often at a defined interval.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] A CRL can also be published immediately after a certificate has been revoked.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] A CRL is issued by a CRL issuer, which is typically the CA which also issued the corresponding certificates, but could alternatively be some other trusted authority.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] All CRLs have a lifetime during which they are valid; this timeframe is often 24 hours or less.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] During a CRL's validity period, it may be consulted by a PKI-enabled application to verify a certificate prior to use.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] To prevent spoofing or denial-of-service attacks, CRLs usually carry a digital signature associated with the CA by which they are published.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] To validate a specific CRL prior to relying on it, the certificate of its corresponding CA is needed.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] The certificates for which a CRL should be maintained are often X.509/public key certificates, as this format is commonly used by PKI schemes.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] Expiration dates are not a substitute for a CRL.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] While all expired certificates are considered invalid, not all unexpired certificates should be valid.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] CRLs or other certificate validation techniques are a necessary part of any properly operated PKI, as mistakes in certificate vetting and key management are expected to occur in real world operations.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] In a noteworthy example, a certificate for Microsoft was mistakenly issued to an unknown individual, who had successfully posed as Microsoft to the CA contracted to maintain the ActiveX 'publisher certificate' system (VeriSign).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] Microsoft saw the need to patch their cryptography subsystem so it would check the status of certificates before trusting them.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] As a short-term fix, a patch was issued for the relevant Microsoft software (most importantly Windows) specifically listing the two certificates in question as "revoked".
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] Best practices require that wherever and however certificate status is maintained, it must be checked whenever one wants to rely on a certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] Failing this, a revoked certificate may be incorrectly accepted as valid.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] This means that to use a PKI effectively, one must have access to current CRLs.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] This requirement of on-line validation negates one of the original major advantages of PKI over symmetric cryptography protocols, namely that the certificate is "self-authenticating".
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] Symmetric systems such as Kerberos also depend on the existence of on-line services (a key distribution center in the case of Kerberos).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] The existence of a CRL implies the need for someone (or some organization) to enforce policy and revoke certificates deemed counter to operational policy.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] If a certificate is mistakenly revoked, significant problems can arise.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] As the certificate authority is tasked with enforcing the operational policy for issuing certificates, they typically are responsible for determining if and when revocation is appropriate by interpreting the operational policy.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] The necessity of consulting a CRL (or other certificate status service) prior to accepting a certificate raises a potential denial-of-service attack against the PKI.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] If acceptance of a certificate fails in the absence of an available valid CRL, then no operations depending upon certificate acceptance can take place.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] This issue exists for Kerberos systems as well, where failure to retrieve a current authentication token will prevent system access.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] An alternative to using CRLs is the certificate validation protocol known as Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] OCSP has the primary benefit of requiring less network bandwidth, enabling real-time and near real-time status checks for high volume or high-value operations.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] As of Firefox 28, Mozilla has announced they are deprecating CRL in favour of OCSP.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] CRL files may grow quite large over time e.g. in US government, for certain institution multiple megabytes.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] Therefore, incremental CRLs have been designed sometimes referred to as "delta CRLs".
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] However, only a few clients implement them.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-revocation-list] An *authority revocation list* (ARL) is a form of CRL containing revoked certificates issued to certificate authorities, contrary to CRLs which contain revoked end-entity certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] In public key infrastructure (PKI) systems, a **certificate signing request** (**CSR** or **certification request**) is a message sent from an applicant to a certificate authority of the public key infrastructure (PKI) in order to apply for a digital identity certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The CSR usually contains the public key for which the certificate should be issued, identifying information (such as a holder or domain name) and a proof of possession of the corresponding private key (typically in the form of a digital signature, which includes integrity protection).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The most common format for CSRs is the **PKCS #10** specification, first published in November 1993; others include the more capable Certificate Request Message Format (CRMF) and the SPKAC (Signed Public Key and Challenge) format generated by some web browsers.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] Note that neither of the CSR formats authenticate the identity of the requester.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The proof of origin of the request must be achieved and verified by other means (typically using a certificate enrollment protocol such as CMP, EST, or ACME), otherwise the obtained certificate has no real security value.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The CSR contains information identifying the applicant (such as a distinguished name), the public key chosen by the applicant, and possibly further information.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] When using the PKCS #10 format, the request must be self-signed using the applicant's private key, which provides proof of possession (POP) of the private key but limits the use of this format to keys that can be used for (some form of) signing.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The CSR must be accompanied by a proof of origin (i.e., proof of identity of the applicant), which is required for security reasons by the certificate authority.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The certificate authority may contact the applicant for further information.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] Typical information required in a CSR (sample column from sample X.509 certificate).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] Note that there are often alternatives for the Distinguished Names (DN), the preferred value is listed.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The CSR is typically sent to a Registration Authority (RA), which checks the CSR contents and authenticates the applicant.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] On success the CSR is forwarded to a Certificate Authority (CA), which produces the X.509 public-key certificate, digitally signing it using the CA private key, and sends the new certificate to the applicant.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] A certification request in PKCS #10 format consists of three main parts: the certification request information, a signature algorithm identifier, and a digital signature on the certification request information using the private key related to the public key being certified.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The signature constitutes a self-signature with the key pair of the applicant.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] Due to the self-signature requirement, this format is applicable only to types of keys that support signing.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] Yet there are variants of this format that do not include an actual signature, such as described in Appendix C.1 of RFC 5272 (CMS).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The first part contains as its most significant information the public key and the identity of the applicant.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The self-signature by the applicant provides a proof of possession (POP).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] Checking the POP prevents an entity from requesting a bogus certificate of someone else's public key.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] Thus the private key is required to produce a PKCS #10 CSR.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] Yet note that the POP for the key pair by the subject entity does not provide any authentication of the subject entity.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The proof of origin for the request by the applicant must therefore be provided and checked by other means.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] Otherwise illegitimate certificates can be produced where the subject/holder information is wrong.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] CSR for personal ID certificates and signing certificates usually includes the email address of the ID holder or the name of organisation in case of business ID.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The attributes can contain required certificate extensions, a challenge-password to restrict revocations, as well as any additional information about the subject of the certificate, possibly including local or future types.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] The PKCS#10 standard defines syntax, semantics, and binary format for CSRs for use with X.509.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/certificate-signing-request] This was generated by supplying the base64 encoding into the command `openssl asn1parse -in *your_request.p10* -inform PEM -i` where PEM (Privacy-Enhanced Mail) is the encoding of the ASN.1 Distinguished Encoding Rules in base64.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] The **Online Certificate Status Protocol** (**OCSP**) is an Internet protocol used for obtaining the revocation status of an X.509 digital certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] It was created as an alternative to certificate revocation lists (CRL), specifically addressing certain problems associated with using CRLs in a public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Messages communicated via OCSP are encoded in ASN.1 and are usually communicated over HTTP.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] The "request/response" nature of these messages leads to OCSP servers being termed *OCSP responders*.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Some web browsers (e.g., Firefox) use OCSP to validate HTTPS certificates, while others have disabled it.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Most OCSP revocation statuses on the Internet disappear soon after certificate expiration.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Certificate authorities (CAs) were previously required by the CA/Browser Forum to provide OCSP service, but this requirement was removed in July 2023, making OCSP optional and CRLs required again.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] On August 6, 2025, Let's Encrypt announced that OCSP services will be shut down due to privacy concerns.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Alice wishes to perform a transaction with Bob and sends him her certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Bob, concerned that Alice's private key may have been compromised, creates an 'OCSP request' that contains Alice's certificate serial number and sends it to Carol.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Carol's OCSP responder reads the certificate serial number from Bob's request.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] The OCSP responder uses the certificate serial number to look up the revocation status of Alice's certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] The OCSP responder looks in a CA database that Carol maintains.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] In this scenario, Carol's CA database is the only trusted location where a compromise to Alice's certificate would be recorded.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Carol's OCSP responder confirms that Alice's certificate is still OK, and returns a signed, successful 'OCSP response' to Bob.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Bob cryptographically verifies Carol's signed response.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Bob has stored Carol's public key some time before this transaction.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Bob uses Carol's public key to verify Carol's response.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Bob completes the transaction with Alice.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] An OCSP responder (a server typically run by the certificate issuer) may return a signed response signifying that the certificate specified in the request is 'good', 'revoked', or 'unknown'.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] If it cannot process the request, it may return an error code.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] The OCSP request format supports additional extensions.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] This enables extensive customization to a particular PKI scheme.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] OCSP can be vulnerable to replay attacks, where a signed, 'good' response is captured by a malicious intermediary and replayed to the client at a later date after the subject certificate may have been revoked.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] OCSP allows a nonce to be included in the request that may be included in the corresponding response.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Because of high load, most OCSP responders do not use the nonce extension to create a different response for each request, instead using presigned responses with a validity period of multiple days.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Thus, the replay attack is a major threat to validation systems.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] OCSP can support more than one level of CA.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] OCSP requests may be chained between peer responders to query the issuing CA appropriate for the subject certificate, with responders validating each other's responses against the root CA using their own OCSP requests.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] An OCSP responder may be queried for revocation information by delegated path validation (DPV) servers.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] OCSP does not, by itself, perform any DPV of supplied certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] The key that signs a response need not be the same key that signed the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] The certificate's issuer may delegate another authority to be the OCSP responder.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] OCSP checking creates a privacy concern for some users, since it requires the client to contact a third party (albeit a party trusted by the client software vendor) to confirm certificate validity.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] This third party could thus track what websites the client is accessing.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] OCSP stapling is a way to verify validity without disclosing browsing behavior to the CA.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] OCSP-based revocation is not an effective technique to mitigate against the compromise of an HTTPS server's private key.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] An attacker who has compromised a server's private key typically needs to be in a man-in-the-middle position on the network to abuse that private key and impersonate a server.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] An attacker in such a position is also typically in a position to interfere with the client's OCSP queries.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Because most clients will silently ignore OCSP if the query times out, OCSP is not a reliable means of mitigating HTTPS server key compromise.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] The MustStaple TLS extension in a certificate can require that the certificate be verified by a stapled OCSP response, mitigating this problem.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] OCSP also remains a valid defense against situations where the attacker is not a "man-in-the-middle" (code-signing or certificates issued in error).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] The OCSP protocol assumes the requester has network access to connect to an appropriate OCSP responder.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Some requesters may not be able to connect because their local network prohibits direct Internet access (a common practice for internal nodes in a data center).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Forcing internal servers to connect to the Internet in order to use OCSP contributes to the de-perimeterisation trend.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] The OCSP stapling protocol is an alternative that allows servers to cache OCSP responses, which removes the need for the requestor to directly contact the OCSP responder.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Google disabled OCSP checks by default in 2012, citing latency and privacy issues and instead uses their own update mechanism to send revoked certificates to the browser.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] Several open source and proprietary OCSP implementations exist, including fully featured servers and libraries for building custom applications.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/online-certificate-status-protocol] OCSP client support is built into many operating systems, web browsers, and other network software due to the popularity of HTTPS and the World Wide Web.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In cryptography, a **public-key certificate**, also known as a **digital certificate** or **identity certificate**, is an electronic document used to prove the valid attribution of a public key to the identity of its holder.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The certificate includes the public key and information about it, information about the identity of its owner (called the subject), and the digital signature of an entity that has verified the certificate's contents (called the issuer).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] If the party examining the certificate trusts the issuer and finds the signature to be a valid signature of that issuer, then it can use the included public key to interact securely with the certificate's subject.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In email encryption, code signing, and e-signature systems, a certificate's subject is typically a person or organization.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] However, in Transport Layer Security (TLS) a certificate's subject is typically a computer or other device, though TLS certificates may identify organizations or individuals in addition to their core role in identifying devices.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] TLS, sometimes called by its older name Secure Sockets Layer (SSL), is notable for being a part of HTTPS, a protocol for securely browsing the web.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In a typical public-key infrastructure (PKI) scheme, the certificate issuer is a certificate authority (CA), usually a company that charges customers a fee to issue certificates for them.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] By contrast, in a web of trust scheme, individuals sign each other's keys directly, in a format that performs a similar function to a public-key certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate is typically requested from a PKI using a CSR, which needs to be transferred using a secure certificate enrollment protocol such as CMP, EST, or ACME.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The parties involved in the enrollment process must verify the authenticity, integrity, and authorization of the CSR, for which the certificate issuer bears the main responsibility.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In case of key compromise or other situations that may lead to unauthorized use, a certificate may need to be revoked.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The general format for public-key and attribute certificates is defined by X.509.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] For public-key certificates, the format has been profiled by the IETF for Internet-related use cases, such as Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A digital certificate system provides a chain of trust, meaning most certificates can be validated against parent certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The chain starts with a **root certificate**, which serves as a trust anchor (a.k.a. root of trust).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] This certificate is self-signed (see below) and has no parent.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The issuing certificate authority uses other methods to safeguard and validate this certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] An **intermediate certificate** has a purpose similar to that of the root certificate – its only use is to sign other certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] However, an intermediate certificate is not self-signed.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A root certificate or another intermediate certificate needs to sign it.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] An **end-entity certificate**, or **leaf certificate**, is any certificate that cannot sign other certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] For instance, TLS/SSL server and client certificates, email certificates, code signing certificates, and qualified certificates are all end-entity certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol – as well as its outdated predecessor, the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) protocol – ensures that the communication between a client computer and a server is secure.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The protocol requires the server to present a digital certificate, proving that it is the intended destination.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A trusted certificate authority has signed the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The *Subject* field of the certificate must identify the primary hostname of the server as the *Common Name*.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] This means that the name listed in the certificate should exactly match the domain name users connect to (for example, `www.example.com`), ensuring that the certificate is valid for that specific hostname.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The hostname must be publicly accessible, not using private addresses or reserved domains.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be valid for multiple hostnames (e.g., a domain and its subdomains).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Such certificates are commonly called *Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates* or *Unified Communications Certificates (UCC)*.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] These certificates contain the Subject Alternative Name field, though many CAs also put them into the *Subject Common Name* field for backward compatibility.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] If some of the hostnames contain an asterisk (*), a certificate may also be called a wildcard certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Once the certification path validation is successful, the client can establish an encrypted connection with the server.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Internet-facing servers, such as public Web servers, must obtain their certificates from a trusted, public certificate authority (CA).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Client certificates authenticate the client connecting to a TLS service, for instance to provide access control.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Because most services provide access to individuals, rather than devices, most client certificates contain an email address or personal name rather than a hostname.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In addition, the certificate authority that issues the client certificate is usually the service provider to which client connects because it is the provider that needs to perform authentication.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] While most web browsers support client certificates, the most common form of authentication on the Internet is a username and password pair.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Client certificates are more common in virtual private networks (VPN) and Remote Desktop Services, where they authenticate devices.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In accordance with the S/MIME protocol, email certificates can both establish the message integrity and encrypt messages.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] To establish encrypted email communication, the communicating parties must have their digital certificates in advance.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Each must send the other one digitally signed email and opt to import the sender's certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Some publicly trusted certificate authorities provide email certificates, but more commonly S/MIME is used when communicating within a given organization, and that organization runs its own CA, which is trusted by participants in that email system.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A self-signed certificate is a certificate with a subject that matches its issuer, and a signature that can be verified by its own public key.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Although this type of certificate is worthless for establishing remote trust between unacquainted parties, it has full trust value when the issuer and the sole user are the same entity.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] As discussed above (in § Chain of trust), a root certificate is a self-signed certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The certificate authority, which is the sole user of the certificate, uses other means to validate and safeguard it.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Another example is the Encrypting File System on Microsoft Windows, which issues a self-signed certificate on behalf of the encrypting user, and uses it to transparently decrypt data on the fly.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates are an extension to X.509 that allows various values to be associated with a security certificate using a `subjectAltName` field.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] These values are called *Subject Alternative Names* (SANs).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] As of May 2000, Subject Alternative Names are the preferred method of adding DNS names to certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The previous method of putting DNS names in the `commonName` field is now deprecated.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Google Chrome version 58 (March 2017) removed support for checking the `commonName` field at all, instead only looking at the SANs.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] As shown in the picture of Wikimedia's section on the right, the SAN field can contain wildcards.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Not all vendors support or endorse mixing wildcards into SAN certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate which uses an asterisk `*` (the *wildcard*) in the domain name portion of it subject is called a Wildcard certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Through the use of `*`, a single certificate may be used for multiple sub-domains.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] It is commonly used for transport layer security in computer networking.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Instead of getting separate certificates for subdomains, you can use a single certificate for all main domains and subdomains and reduce cost.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Note possible exceptions by CAs, for example wildcard-plus cert by DigiCert contains an automatic "Plus" property for the naked domain `example.com`.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Only a single level of subdomain matching is supported.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] It is not possible to get a wildcard for an Extended Validation Certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A workaround could be to add every virtual host name in the Subject Alternative Name (SAN) extension, the major problem being that the certificate needs to be reissued whenever a new virtual server is added.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Wildcards can be added as domains in multi-domain certificates or Unified Communications Certificates (UCC).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In addition, wildcards themselves can have `subjectAltName` extensions, including other wildcards.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] For example, the wildcard certificate `*.wikipedia.org` has `*.m.wikimedia.org` as a Subject Alternative Name.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Thus it secures `www.wikipedia.org` as well as the completely different website name `meta.m.wikimedia.org`.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] RFC 6125 argues against wildcard certificates on security grounds, in particular "partial wildcards".
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The wildcard applies only to one level of the domain name.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] However, use of "partial-wildcard" certs is not recommended.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] As of 2011, partial wildcard support is optional, and is explicitly disallowed in SubjectAltName headers that are required for multi-name certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] All major browsers have deliberately **removed** support for partial-wildcard certificates; they will result in a "SSL_ERROR_BAD_CERT_DOMAIN" error.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Similarly, it is typical for standard libraries in programming languages to not support "partial-wildcard" certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] For example, any "partial-wildcard" certificate will not work with the latest versions of both Python and Go.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A cert with multiple wildcards in a name is not allowed.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A cert with `*` plus a top-level domain is not allowed.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] International domain names encoded in ASCII (A-label) are labels that are ASCII-encoded and begin with `xn--`.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] URLs with international labels cannot contain wildcards.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] These are some of the most common fields in certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Most certificates contain a number of fields not listed here.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Note that in terms of a certificate's X.509 representation, a certificate is not "flat" but contains these fields nested in various structures within the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] This is an example of a decoded SSL/TLS certificate retrieved from SSL.com's website.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The issuer's common name (CN) is shown as `SSL.com EV SSL Intermediate CA RSA R3`, identifying this as an Extended Validation (EV) certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Validated information about the website's owner (SSL Corp) is located in the `Subject` field.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Subject Alternative Name` field contains a list of domain names covered by the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Extended Key Usage` and `X509v3 Key Usage` fields show all appropriate uses.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In the European Union, (advanced) electronic signatures on legal documents are commonly performed using digital signatures with accompanying identity certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] However, only qualified electronic signatures (which require using a qualified trust service provider and signature creation device) are given the same power as a physical signature.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In the X.509 trust model, a certificate authority (CA) is responsible for signing certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] These certificates act as an introduction between two parties, which means that a CA acts as a trusted third party.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A CA processes requests from people or organizations requesting certificates (called subscribers), verifies the information, and potentially signs an end-entity certificate based on that information.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] To perform this role effectively, a CA needs to have one or more broadly trusted root certificates or intermediate certificates and the corresponding private keys.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] CAs may achieve this broad trust by having their root certificates included in popular software, or by obtaining a cross-signature from another CA delegating trust.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Other CAs are trusted within a relatively small community, like a business, and are distributed by other mechanisms like Windows Group Policy.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Certificate authorities are also responsible for maintaining up-to-date revocation information about certificates they have issued, indicating whether certificates are still valid.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] They provide this information through Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) and/or Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Some of the larger certificate authorities in the market include IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Some major software contain a list of certificate authorities that are trusted by default.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] This makes it easier for end-users to validate certificates, and easier for people or organizations that request certificates to know which certificate authorities can issue a certificate that will be broadly trusted.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] This is particularly important in HTTPS, where a web site operator generally wants to get a certificate that is trusted by nearly all potential visitors to their web site.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The policies and processes a provider uses to decide which certificate authorities their software should trust are called root programs.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Browsers other than Firefox generally use the operating system's facilities to decide which certificate authorities are trusted.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] So, for instance, Chrome on Windows trusts the certificate authorities included in the Microsoft Root Program, while on macOS or iOS, Chrome trusts the certificate authorities in the Apple Root Program.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Edge and Safari use their respective operating system trust stores as well, but each is only available on a single OS.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Firefox uses the Mozilla Root Program trust store on all platforms.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The Mozilla Root Program is operated publicly, and its certificate list is part of the open source Firefox web browser, so it is broadly used outside Firefox.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] For instance, while there is no common Linux Root Program, many Linux distributions, like Debian, include a package that periodically copies the contents of the Firefox trust list, which is then used by applications.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Root programs generally provide a set of valid purposes with the certificates they include.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] For instance, some CAs may be considered trusted for issuing TLS server certificates, but not for code signing certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] This is indicated with a set of trust bits in a root certificate storage system.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Revocation is performed by the issuing certificate authority, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The most common use of certificates is for HTTPS-based web sites.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A web browser validates that an HTTPS web server is authentic, so that the user can feel secure that his/her interaction with the web site has no eavesdroppers and that the web site is who it claims to be.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] This security is important for electronic commerce.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In practice, a web site operator obtains a certificate by applying to a certificate authority with a certificate signing request.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The certificate request is an electronic document that contains the web site name, company information and the public key.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The certificate provider signs the request, thus producing a public certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] During web browsing, this public certificate is served to any web browser that connects to the web site and proves to the web browser that the provider believes it has issued a certificate to the owner of the web site.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Further, the relationship between the purchaser of the certificate, the operator of the web site, and the generator of the web site content may be tenuous and is not guaranteed.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] At best, the certificate guarantees uniqueness of the web site, provided that the web site itself has not been compromised (hacked) or the certificate issuing process subverted.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider can opt to issue three types of certificates, each requiring its own degree of vetting rigor.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In order of increasing rigor (and naturally, cost) they are: Domain Validation, Organization Validation and Extended Validation.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] These rigors are loosely agreed upon by voluntary participants in the CA/Browser Forum.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue a domain-validated (DV) certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can demonstrate one vetting criterion: the right to administratively manage the affected DNS domain(s).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue an organization validation (OV) class certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can meet two criteria: the right to administratively manage the domain name in question, and perhaps, the organization's actual existence as a legal entity.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider publishes its OV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] To acquire an Extended Validation (EV) certificate, the purchaser must persuade the certificate provider of its legal identity, including manual verification checks by a human.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] As with OV certificates, a certificate provider publishes its EV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Until 2019, major browsers such as Chrome and Firefox generally offered users a visual indication of the legal identity when a site presented an EV certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] This was done by showing the legal name before the domain, and a bright green color to highlight the change.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Most browsers deprecated this feature providing no visual difference to the user on the type of certificate used.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] This change followed security concerns raised by forensic experts and successful attempts to purchase EV certificates to impersonate famous organizations, proving the inefficiency of these visual indicators and highlighting potential abuses.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] A web browser will give no warning to the user if a web site suddenly presents a different certificate, even if that certificate has a lower number of key bits, even if it has a different provider, and even if the previous certificate had an expiry date far into the future.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Where certificate providers are under the jurisdiction of governments, those governments may have the freedom to order the provider to generate any certificate, such as for the purposes of law enforcement.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Subsidiary wholesale certificate providers also have the freedom to generate any certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] All web browsers come with an extensive built-in list of trusted root certificates, many of which are controlled by organizations that may be unfamiliar to the user.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] Each of these organizations is free to issue any certificate for any web site and have the guarantee that web browsers that include its root certificates will accept it as genuine.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In this instance, end users must rely on the developer of the browser software to manage its built-in list of certificates and on the certificate providers to behave correctly and to inform the browser developer of problematic certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] While uncommon, there have been incidents in which fraudulent certificates have been issued: in some cases, the browsers have detected the fraud; in others, some time passed before browser developers removed these certificates from their software.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] The list of built-in certificates is also not limited to those provided by the browser developer: users (and to a degree applications) are free to extend the list for special purposes such as for company intranets.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] This means that if someone gains access to a machine and can install a new root certificate in the browser, that browser will recognize websites that use the inserted certificate as legitimate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] For provable security, this reliance on something external to the system has the consequence that any public-key certification scheme has to rely on some special setup assumption, such as the existence of a certificate authority.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] In spite of the limitations described above, certificate-authenticated TLS is considered mandatory by all security guidelines whenever a web site hosts confidential information or performs material transactions.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-certificate] This is because, in practice, in spite of the weaknesses described above, web sites secured by public-key certificates are still more secure than unsecured http:// web sites.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] A **public key infrastructure** (**PKI**) is a set of roles, policies, hardware, software and procedures used to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key cryptography set-ups.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] In cryptography, a PKI is an arrangement that *binds* public keys with respective identities of entities (like people and organizations).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] The binding is established through a process of registration and issuance of certificates at and by a certificate authority (CA).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Depending on the assurance level of the binding, this may be carried out by an automated process or under human supervision.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] When done over a network, this requires using a secure certificate enrollment or certificate management protocol such as CMP.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI role that may be delegated by a CA to assure valid and correct registration is called a *registration authority* (RA).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] An RA is responsible for accepting requests for digital certificates and authenticating the entity making the request.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] RAs, however, do not sign or issue certificates (i.e., an RA is delegated certain tasks on behalf of a CA)." While Microsoft may have referred to a subordinate CA as an RA, this is incorrect according to the X.509 PKI standards.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] RAs do not have the signing authority of a CA and only manage the vetting and provisioning of certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] In the case of Microsoft Standalone CAs, the function of RA does not exist since all of the procedures controlling the CA are based on the administration and access procedure associated with the system hosting the CA and the CA itself rather than Active Directory.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Most non-Microsoft commercial PKI solutions offer a stand-alone RA component.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] An entity must be uniquely identifiable within each CA domain on the basis of information about that entity.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] A third-party validation authority (VA) can provide this entity information on behalf of the CA.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] The X.509 standard defines the most commonly used format for public key certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] PKI provides "trust services" - in plain terms trusting the actions or outputs of entities, be they people or computers.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Trust service objectives respect one or more of the following capabilities: Confidentiality, Integrity and Authenticity (CIA).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Public-key cryptography is a cryptographic technique that enables entities to securely communicate on an insecure public network, and reliably verify the identity of an entity via digital signatures.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] A public key infrastructure (PKI) is a system for the creation, storage, and distribution of digital certificates, which are used to verify that a particular public key belongs to a certain entity.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI creates digital certificates that map public keys to entities, securely stores these certificates in a central repository and revokes them if needed.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] The primary role of the CA is to digitally sign and publish the public key bound to a given user.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] This is done using the CA's own private key, so that trust in the user key relies on one's trust in the validity of the CA's key.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] When the CA is a third party separate from the user and the system, then it is called the Registration Authority (RA), which may or may not be separate from the CA.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] The key-to-user binding is established, depending on the level of assurance the binding has, by software or under human supervision.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] The term trusted third party (TTP) may also be used for certificate authority (CA).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Moreover, PKI is itself often used as a synonym for a CA implementation.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or mis-issued certificate until expiry.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] In this model of trust relationships, a CA is a trusted third party – trusted both by the subject (owner) of the certificate and by the party relying upon the certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Following major issues in how certificate issuing was managed, all major players gradually distrusted Symantec-issued certificates, starting in 2017 and completed in 2021.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] This approach involves a server that acts as an offline certificate authority within a single sign-on system.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] A single sign-on server will issue digital certificates into the client system, but never stores them.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Users can execute programs, etc. with the temporary certificate.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] It is common to find this solution variety with X.509-based certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Starting Sep 2020, TLS Certificate Validity reduced to 13 Months.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] An alternative approach to the problem of public authentication of public key information is the web-of-trust scheme, which uses self-signed certificates and third-party attestations of those certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] The singular term "web of trust" does not imply the existence of a single web of trust, or common point of trust, but rather one of any number of potentially disjoint "webs of trust".
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Examples of implementations of this approach are PGP (Pretty Good Privacy) and GnuPG (an implementation of OpenPGP, the standardized specification of PGP).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Because PGP and implementations allow the use of e-mail digital signatures for self-publication of public key information, it is relatively easy to implement one's own web of trust.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] One of the benefits of the web of trust, such as in PGP, is that it can interoperate with a PKI CA fully trusted by all parties in a domain (such as an internal CA in a company) that is willing to guarantee certificates, as a trusted introducer.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] If the "web of trust" is completely trusted then, because of the nature of a web of trust, trusting one certificate is granting trust to all the certificates in that web.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI is only as valuable as the standards and practices that control the issuance of certificates and including PGP or a personally instituted web of trust could significantly degrade the trustworthiness of that enterprise's or domain's implementation of PKI.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Another alternative, which does not deal with public authentication of public key information, is the simple public key infrastructure (SPKI), which grew out of three independent efforts to overcome the complexities of X.509 and PGP's web of trust.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not associate users with persons, since the *key* is what is trusted, rather than the person.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not use any notion of trust, as the verifier is also the issuer.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] This is called an "authorization loop" in SPKI terminology, where authorization is integral to its design.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] This type of PKI is specially useful for making integrations of PKI that do not rely on third parties for certificate authorization, certificate information, etc.; a good example of this is an air-gapped network in an office.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Decentralized identifiers (DIDs) eliminate dependence on centralized registries for identifiers as well as centralized certificate authorities for key management, which is the standard in hierarchical PKI.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] In cases where the DID registry is a distributed ledger, each entity can serve as its own root authority.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] This architecture is referred to as decentralized PKI (DPKI).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Developments in PKI occurred in the early 1970s at the British intelligence agency GCHQ, where James Ellis, Clifford Cocks and others made important discoveries related to encryption algorithms and key distribution.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Because developments at GCHQ are highly classified, the results of this work were kept secret and not publicly acknowledged until the mid-1990s.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] The public disclosure of both secure key exchange and asymmetric key algorithms in 1976 by Diffie, Hellman, Rivest, Shamir, and Adleman changed secure communications entirely.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Assorted cryptographic protocols were invented and analyzed within which the new cryptographic primitives could be effectively used.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] With the invention of the World Wide Web and its rapid spread, the need for authentication and secure communication became still more acute.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Commercial reasons alone (e.g., e-commerce, online access to proprietary databases from web browsers) were sufficient.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Taher Elgamal and others at Netscape developed the SSL protocol ('https' in Web URLs); it included key establishment, server authentication (prior to v3, one-way only), and so on.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI structure was thus created for Web users/sites wishing secure communications.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Vendors and entrepreneurs saw the possibility of a large market, started companies (or new projects at existing companies), and began to agitate for legal recognition and protection from liability.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Consumer groups raised questions about privacy, access, and liability considerations, which were more taken into consideration in some jurisdictions than in others.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] The enacted laws and regulations differed, and there were technical and operational problems in converting PKI schemes into successful commercial operation.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Progress has been much slower than pioneers had imagined it would be.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] By the first few years of the 21st century, the underlying cryptographic engineering was clearly not easy to deploy correctly.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Operating procedures (manual or automatic) were not easy to correctly design (nor even if so designed, to execute perfectly, which the engineering required).
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] The standards that existed were insufficient.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] PKI vendors have found a market, but it is not quite the market envisioned in the mid-1990s, and it has grown both more slowly and in somewhat different ways than were anticipated.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] PKIs have not solved some of the problems they were expected to, and several major vendors have gone out of business or been acquired by others.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] PKI has had the most success in government implementations; the largest PKI implementation to date is the Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) PKI infrastructure for the Common Access Cards program.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Some argue that purchasing certificates for securing websites by SSL/TLS and securing software by code signing is a costly venture for small businesses.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] However, the emergence of free alternatives, such as Let's Encrypt, has changed this.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] HTTP/2, the latest version of HTTP protocol, allows unsecured connections in theory; in practice, major browser companies have made it clear that they would support this protocol only over a PKI secured TLS connection.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Web browser implementation of HTTP/2 including Chrome, Firefox, Opera, and Edge supports HTTP/2 only over TLS by using the ALPN extension of the TLS protocol.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] This would mean that, to get the speed benefits of HTTP/2, website owners would be forced to purchase SSL/TLS certificates controlled by corporations.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Currently the majority of web browsers are shipped with pre-installed intermediate certificates issued and signed by a certificate authority, by public keys certified by so-called root certificates.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] This means browsers need to carry a large number of different certificate providers, increasing the risk of a key compromise.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] When a key is known to be compromised, it could be fixed by revoking the certificate, but such a compromise is not easily detectable and can be a huge security breach.
[src:certificate-lifecycle/public-key-infrastructure] Browsers have to issue a security patch to revoke intermediary certificates issued by a compromised root certificate authority.
